a Diomedonte] The reading Adiomerita has caused the editors much trouble, and James boldly changes it to Anaxar- chus, of whom a similar story is told (ag. Cic Tusc. ii. 22). De Bury, however, is clearly referring to the story of Zeno's death told by Hermippus (quoted in Diog. L ix. 27), who says that he was brayed in a mortar by the tyrant Diomedon, of whom no mention is found elsewhere. The MSS. point plainly enough to the true reading, which I have restored.
